<TITLE> Habibul Bashar announces retirement </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Mar 22 (bdnews24.com) -- Bangladesh's most successful international captain Habibul Bashar announced Sunday that he was retiring from all cricket. Bashar formally notified the BCB about his decision to end his playing career. "It has been a terrific journey for me and after two decades of international, first class and club cricket I feel I have reached the end of the road. The Port City League (PCL) T20 in Sharjah next week will be my last competition as a player," said Bashar in his letter to the BCB. "It is never easy to give up the game you love so much and especially in my case this moment is very emotional as cricket has been my life. "I thank the BCB for giving me the honour of captaining Bangladesh and for the support throughout my career. I will cherish the memories of my time in the Bangladesh dressing room and my heartfelt gratitude goes out to all the players, coaches, team officials and staff I have had the privilege of knowing and working with. "There will always be a special place in my heart for the fans for their warmth and genuine affection. "As I bid bye I also feel excitement at the way the Bangladesh cricket team is progressing. I wish them every success." BCB president AHM Mustafa Kamal said Bashar's legacy will inspire future generations of Bangladeshi cricketers. "We are indebted to this fantastic cricketer who had instilled belief in the players and inspired them to perform. Under his able leadership Bangladesh had tasted the first Test victory and had progressed to the Super Eight stages of the 2007 Cricket World Cup. With his batting he showed others the way to dominate and score at international level. We hope that he will continue to be associated with Bangladesh cricket after his retirem
